  <processinfo id="aspace_e22d49dd30f0293dc8348c38c19758e6">
    <head>Processing Information</head>
<p>At the time of accessioning a collection-level finding aid was created to describe materials in the collection. Born-digital records housed on a hard-drive were forensically imaged and partially inventoried.</p><p>In 2022 materials on the hard-drive were forensically analyzed and arranged in Forensic Toolkit. The original arrangement of born-digital files was retained and analog video cassettes were intellectually incorporated into Series I.</p><p>New York University Libraries follow professional standards and best practices when imaging, ingesting, and processing born-digital material in order to maintain the integrity of the content.</p>  </processinfo>
  <scopecontent id="aspace_18d38db25e98b017723a60b62d272b0f">
    <head>Scope and Contents</head>
<p>The Pamela Sporn Papers consist of videos and research materials used by Pamela Sporn in her documentary films. The bulk of the collection consists of approximately 400 digital video files created by Sporn for her film <emph render="italic">A Humble Giant: 70 Years Defending Immigrants and Radicals</emph>, about immigration lawyer Ira Gollobin. These files include interviews and background footage from the documentary, which have been arranged by Sporn by individual and topic. There is also video footage from Ira Gollobin's 2008 memorial service and a 2005 National Lawyers Guild dinner. The collection also includes research files, budgets, fundraising, and promotional materials related to the production of the documentary. In addition to the digital video files, there are DVCAM and MiniDV cassettes that contain additional interviews. </p><p>The collection also contains DVDs of Sporn's documentaries <emph render="italic">With a Stroke of the Chaveta</emph> and <emph render="italic">Disobeying Orders: GI Resistance to the Vietnam War</emph>, both of which were produced by her small production company Grito Productions. The collection also includes MiniDV video cassettes of interviews Sporn conducted while producing <emph render="italic">With a Stroke of Chaveta</emph>, which documents the experiences of workers in Cuban cigar factories. </p><p>Other materials included in this collection consist of photocopies related to the website Unfriendly Witness: Standing Up to HUAC, which Sporn created to document her family's experience with the House Committee on Un-American Activities (HUAC).</p>  </scopecontent>
  <phystech id="aspace_58072927eac9b81b11dfbd56f37bc762">
    <head>Audiovisual Access Policies and Procedures</head>
<p>Audiovisual materials have not been preserved and may not be available to researchers. Materials not yet digitized will need to have access copies made before they can be used. To request an access copy, or if you are unsure if an item has been digitized, please contact tamiment.wagner@nyu.edu with the collection name, collection number, and a description of the item(s) requested. A staff member will respond to you with further information.</p>  </phystech>
  <phystech id="aspace_deaf9af667ad85202f7ebea5a690f0d9">
    <head>Born-Digital Access Policies and Procedures</head>
<p>An access terminal for born-digital materials in the collection is available by appointment for reading room viewing and listening only. Researchers may view an item's original container and/or carrier, but the physical carriers themselves are not available for use because of preservation concerns.</p>  </phystech>
  <userestrict id="aspace_12866d23120c91832ad024e99581debf">
    <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
<p>Copyright (or related rights to publicity and privacy) for materials in this collection, created by Pamela Sporn, was not transferred to New York University. Permission to use materials must be secured from the copyright holder.</p>  </userestrict>
  <relatedmaterial id="aspace_e71a6a0da71e3dbc2e57eeaffb38b084">
    <head>Related Materials</head>
<p>For more information about Ira Gollobin please see the Ira Gollobin Papers (TAM 278) and the Records of the American Committee for Protection of Foreign Born (TAM 086), both held by New York University Special Collections. There is also a collection of Ira Gollobin's papers at the New York Public Library Archives and Manuscripts (MssCol 6133).</p>  </relatedmaterial>
