  <dsc><c id="aspace_a6b54386ea434baed9bfefc295a68380" level="series"><did><unittitle>Series I: <emph render= 'italic'>A Humble Giant</emph> media</unittitle><physdesc altrender="part"><extent altrender="materialtype spaceoccupied">2 videocassettes (dvcam)</extent></physdesc><physdesc altrender="part"><extent altrender="materialtype spaceoccupied">23 videocassettes (minidv)</extent></physdesc><physdesc altrender="whole"><extent altrender="materialtype spaceoccupied">831 Gigabytes</extent><extent altrender="carrier">in 415 computer files</extent></physdesc><unitdate datechar="creation" normal="2004/2011" type="inclusive">2004-2011</unitdate></did><arrangement id="aspace_eabc87d1422c52477dde638ff0d703ad"><head>Arrangement</head><p>Files are arranged alphabetically.</p></arrangement><scopecontent id="aspace_138bfe0ae40c452f7fa1f8af0bacc968"><head>Scope and Contents</head><p>This series contains video footage of interviews and events Pamela Sporn filmed for the documentary <emph render= 'italic'>A Humble Giant</emph> about immigration attorney Ira Gollobin. Sporn interviewed Gollobin, his wife Ruth Gollobin, and some of his former clients and affiliates including Henry Foner, Bertell Ollman, Albert Socolov, and Sporn's father Paul Sporn. Topics covered include Gollobin's work with people who were targeted by the House Un-American Activities Committee (HUAC), immigrant rights activism, the Abraham Lincoln Brigade and the Spanish Civil War, and issues regarding the Labor movement and Leftist politics. Sporn also filmed much of Gollobin's memorial service which followed his death in 2008.</p><p>The video in this series was filmed digitally. In addition to video files that were stored on a harddrive there are also DVCAM and MiniDV cassettes.</p></scopecontent><c id="aspace_790d2a591c383705bfe6f7bd9415813d" level="file"><did><unittitle>Albert Socolov on Ira Gollobin and the National Lawyers Guild</unittitle><unitid>cuid36873</unitid><unitdate datechar="creation" normal="2010